From: <reviewer>

mm/memcontrol: batch memcg charging in __memcg_slab_post_alloc_hook

I traced the charge/uncharge symmetry, skip_next control flow, vmstat
accounting, and obj_cgroup_get/put symmetry.  The approach is sound.
One type issue is worth fixing before merging.

> diff --git a/mm/memcontrol.c b/mm/memcontrol.c
> --- a/mm/memcontrol.c
> +++ b/mm/memcontrol.c

[ ... ]

> +		struct pglist_data *pgdat;
> +		unsigned int batch_bytes;
> +		size_t run_len = 0;

batch_bytes is declared as unsigned int, but obj_size is size_t and
run_len is size_t.  The multiplication

    batch_bytes = obj_size * run_len;

is evaluated in size_t arithmetic and then silently truncated to
unsigned int on 64-bit builds.  For current callers the product stays
well below 4 GB, but the intermediate should be size_t to match
obj_size and the size_t parameter of __obj_cgroup_charge().
__consume_obj_stock() already takes unsigned int, so the narrowing
would happen at that call site instead of here.

> +		for (j = i + 1; j < size; j++) {
> +			struct slab *slab_j = virt_to_slab(p[j]);
> +			if (slab_pgdat(slab_j) != pgdat)
> +				break;
> +			if (!slab_obj_exts(slab_j) &&
> +			    alloc_slab_obj_exts(slab_j, s, flags, false)) {
> +				skip_next = true;
> +				break;
> +			}
> +			run_len++;
> +		}

I verified the skip_next advance logic:

    if (skip_next)
        i = i + run_len + 1;
    else
        i += run_len;

When alloc_slab_obj_exts() fails at position j, run_len++ has not
been reached (it follows the failure check), so run_len counts objects
i..j-1 only, and i advances to j+1.  The failed object at j is
skipped without any charge being issued, matching the original
continue behaviour.  Double-checked the two-consecutive-failure case:
the outer-loop guard handles the next skipped object independently via
its own i++; continue path.

> +		__account_obj_stock(objcg, stock, batch_bytes,
> +				    pgdat, cache_vmstat_idx(s));

The vmstat accounting is symmetric with __memcg_slab_free_hook(): all
objects in the batch share the same pgdat (enforced by the inner-loop
break), and the free hook unchargess per-object using slab_pgdat(slab)
for each, which resolves to the same pgdat.  Total charged bytes equal
obj_size * run_len; total bytes refilled across individual frees equal
the same.  The obj_cgroup_get() count in the assignment loop is one
per batch object, balanced by one obj_cgroup_put() per object in the
free hook.

From: Chunyu Hu <chuhu@redhat.com>
Subject: [PATCH v2 0/5] selftests/mm: skip several tests when thp is not available

Series looks good.  I verified thp_is_enabled(), the TAP plan accounting
in soft-dirty, the write_file() consolidation, and the placement of
ksft_exit_skip() in each main().

> diff --git a/tools/testing/selftests/mm/soft-dirty.c b/tools/testing/selftests/mm/soft-dirty.c
> @@ -82,7 +82,9 @@ static void test_hugepage(int pagemap_fd, int pagesize)
>  	if (!thp_is_enabled()) {
> -		ksft_test_result_skip("Transparent Hugepages not available\n");
> +		ksft_print_msg("Transparent Hugepages not available\n");
> +		ksft_test_result_skip("Test %s huge page allocation\n", __func__);
> +		ksft_test_result_skip("Test %s huge page dirty bit\n", __func__);
>  		return;
>  	}

Checked: test_hugepage covers exactly two sub-tests (allocation and
dirty-bit), so emitting two skip results keeps the count at the
declared plan of 19.  The old single skip left the harness reporting
"Planned tests != run tests (19 != 18)".

> diff --git a/tools/testing/selftests/mm/thp_settings.c b/tools/testing/selftests/mm/thp_settings.c
> +#include "vm_util.h"
> [ ... ]
> diff --git a/tools/testing/selftests/mm/vm_util.c b/tools/testing/selftests/mm/vm_util.c
> +unsigned int write_file(const char *path, const char *buf, size_t buflen)
> +{
> +	fd = open(path, O_WRONLY);
> +	if (fd == -1)
> +		ksft_exit_fail_msg("%s open failed: %s\n", path, strerror(errno));
> +	numwritten = write(fd, buf, buflen - 1);
> +	close(fd);
> +	if (numwritten < 1)
> +		ksft_exit_fail_msg("Write failed\n");
> +	return (unsigned int) numwritten;
> +}

The new write_file() exits on failure and never returns 0.  The
existing callers in thp_settings.c (write_num and thp_write_string)
both guard with "if (!write_file(...))", making that branch
unreachable dead code.  Not a bug, but a minor cleanup opportunity
if desired.

Checked: split_huge_page_test places ksft_exit_skip() after
ksft_print_header() but before ksft_set_plan(), which is the correct
TAP pattern for a whole-test skip (outputs "1..0 # SKIP ...").
Same for transhuge-stress.  Both match the expected output shown in
the commit messages.

Looks good to me.

From: reviewer

Series: Migrate on fault for device pages (v6)

-- patch 3/6: mm/hmm: do the plumbing for HMM to participate in migration --

> diff --git a/include/linux/migrate.h b/include/linux/migrate.h
> @@ -104,6 +104,15 @@ static inline void softleaf_entry_wait_on_locked(...)
>  	WARN_ON_ONCE(1);
>  
>  	spin_unlock(ptl);
> +
> +enum migrate_vma_info {
> +	MIGRATE_VMA_SELECT_NONE = 0,
> +	MIGRATE_VMA_SELECT_COMPOUND = MIGRATE_VMA_SELECT_NONE,
> +};
> +
> +static inline enum migrate_vma_info hmm_select_migrate(struct hmm_range *range)
> +{
> +	return MIGRATE_VMA_SELECT_NONE;
> +}
>  }

The closing '}' above belongs to softleaf_entry_wait_on_locked(),
so the new enum definition and hmm_select_migrate() stub end up
inside the function body. Defining a static inline function inside
another function body is not valid C; GCC will reject this. The
hunk is off by one brace: the enum and stub should be inserted
after the '}' that closes softleaf_entry_wait_on_locked(), not
before it.

-- patch 5/6: mm: add new testcase for the migrate on fault case --

> +static int do_fault_and_migrate(struct dmirror *dmirror,
> +				struct hmm_range *range)
> +{
> +	struct migrate_vma *migrate = range->migrate;
> +	int ret;
> +
> +	mmap_read_lock(dmirror->notifier.mm);
> +
> +	ret = dmirror_range_fault(dmirror, range);
> +
> +	pr_debug("Migrating from sys mem to device mem\n");
> +	migrate_hmm_range_setup(range);
> +
> +	dmirror_migrate_alloc_and_copy(migrate, dmirror);
> +	migrate_vma_pages(migrate);
> +	dmirror_migrate_finalize_and_map(migrate, dmirror);
> +	migrate_vma_finalize(migrate);

Three issues here:

1. The return value of dmirror_range_fault() is saved in 'ret' but
   the migration sequence runs unconditionally. If the fault fails
   the src/dst arrays may be in a partial state; calling
   migrate_vma_pages() on them is unsafe. A guard like
   'if (ret) goto out_unlock;' is needed before
   migrate_hmm_range_setup().

2. migrate->vma is never initialised in this call chain.
   __migrate_device_pages() dereferences migrate->vma->vm_mm when
   it handles a zero-page entry (src has MIGRATE_PFN_MIGRATE set
   but MIGRATE_PFN_VALID clear). With migrate->vma == NULL the
   first anonymous zero-page hit inside migrate_vma_pages() will
   NULL-deref. The cover letter states migrate_vma.vma gets
   populated by the HMM fault walk -- where exactly does that
   assignment happen before migrate_hmm_range_setup() is called?

> +static int dmirror_fault_and_migrate_to_device(struct dmirror *dmirror,
> +					       struct hmm_dmirror_cmd *cmd)
> +{
> +	unsigned long src_pfns[PFNS_ARRAY_SIZE] = { 0 };
> +	unsigned long dst_pfns[PFNS_ARRAY_SIZE] = { 0 };
> +	struct migrate_vma migrate = { 0 };

[ ... ]

> +	migrate.pgmap_owner = dmirror->mdevice;
> +	migrate.src = src_pfns;
> +	migrate.dst = dst_pfns;
> +	migrate.flags = MIGRATE_VMA_SELECT_SYSTEM;

3. migrate.start and migrate.end are zero-initialised and never
   assigned. migrate_hmm_range_setup() computes npages as
   '(migrate->end - migrate->start) >> PAGE_SHIFT', which is 0,
   so the src/dst fill loop never executes and nothing is ever
   collected for migration. The testcase would silently pass while
   exercising nothing. migrate.start and migrate.end must be set to
   the current range.start/range.end inside the iteration loop,
   before calling do_fault_and_migrate().

Sergey Senozhatsky <senozhatsky@chromium.org>

zram: propagate read_from_bdev_async() errors

Verified the error propagation chain end-to-end:

> -static void read_from_bdev_async(struct zram *zram, struct page *page,
> -				 u32 index, unsigned long blk_idx,
> -				 struct bio *parent)
> +static int read_from_bdev_async(struct zram *zram, struct page *page,
> +				u32 index, unsigned long blk_idx,
> +				struct bio *parent)
>  {
>  	req = kmalloc_obj(*req, GFP_NOIO);
>  	if (!req)
> -		return;
> +		return -ENOMEM;
>  
>  	bio = bio_alloc(zram->bdev, 1, parent->bi_opf, GFP_NOIO);
>  	if (!bio) {
>  		kfree(req);
> -		return;
> +		return -ENOMEM;
>  	}

In both error paths bio_inc_remaining(parent) has not yet been called,
so the parent bio's remaining count is unaffected.  The -ENOMEM flows
up through read_from_bdev() -> zram_read_page() -> zram_bvec_read() ->
zram_bio_read(), where bi_status is set to BLK_STS_IOERR and
bio_endio() completes the parent correctly.

> -	read_from_bdev_async(zram, page, index, blk_idx, parent);
> -	return 0;
> +	return read_from_bdev_async(zram, page, index, blk_idx, parent);

The sync path already propagated errors via read_from_bdev_sync();
this brings the async path into line.  Looks good.

From: &lt;reviewer&gt;
Subject: Re: [PATCH v2] mm/damon/stat: monitor all System RAM resources

&gt; +static int damon_stat_system_ram_walk_fn(struct resource *res, void *arg)
&gt; +{
&gt; +	struct damon_stat_system_ram_range_walk_arg *a = arg;
&gt; +
&gt; +	if (!a-&gt;walked) {
&gt; +		a-&gt;walked = true;
&gt; +		a-&gt;res.start = res-&gt;start;
&gt; +	}
&gt; +	a-&gt;res.end = res-&gt;end;
&gt; +	return 0;
&gt; +}

walk_system_ram_res() traverses resources in ascending address order,
so recording res-&gt;start only on the first call and unconditionally
updating res-&gt;end gives us the span [first_RAM_start, last_RAM_end].
Verified correct.

[ ... ]

&gt; +static unsigned long damon_stat_res_to_core_addr(resource_size_t ra,
&gt; +		unsigned long addr_unit)
&gt; +{
&gt; +	if (sizeof(ra) == 8 &amp;&amp; sizeof(addr_unit) == 4)
&gt; +		return div_u64(ra, addr_unit);
&gt; +	return ra / addr_unit;
&gt; +}

This is a verbatim copy of the static damon_res_to_core_addr() in
core.c, which is not reachable from stat.c.  Could
damon_res_to_core_addr() be made non-static (or lifted to a shared
header) to avoid the duplication?  Not a blocker, but worth a
follow-up.

[ ... ]

&gt; +	return damon_set_regions(t, &amp;addr_range, 1, min_region_sz);

Passing 1 as nr_ranges is correct.  As an aside, the function being
replaced -- damon_set_region_biggest_system_ram_default() in core.c --
has a pre-existing bug at its own damon_set_regions() call site:

  return damon_set_regions(t, &amp;addr_range, addr_unit, min_region_sz);

It passes addr_unit where the unsigned int nr_ranges argument is
expected.  When addr_unit is 1 (byte-granular) this works by
coincidence, but for any other value damon_set_regions() would iterate
well past the single-element addr_range on the stack.  This patch
avoids the bug for stat.c, but damon_reclaim and damon_lru_sort still
call that function; a separate fix may be warranted.
